Import necessary libraries such as OpenCV, numpy, pandas, and argparse.
Read an image using the OpenCV imread() function.
Define global variables for clicked, r, g, b, xpos, and ypos.
Read the CSV file containing color names and values using pandas read_csv() function.
Define a function to calculate the minimum distance from all colors and return the most matching color name.
Define a function to get x and y coordinates of the mouse double click.
Create a window and bind the draw_function() function to it using the OpenCV namedWindow() and setMouseCallback() functions.
Continuously show the image and wait for a mouse double click event.
When a mouse double click event occurs, get the RGB values of the pixel where the event occurred.
Create a rectangle and display the RGB values in it.
Use the getColorName() function to get the color name based on the RGB values.
Create a text string containing the color name and RGB values.
Display the text string using the OpenCV putText() function.
If the color is very light, display the text string in black color.
If the 'esc' key is pressed, break the loop and close the window.
